#Text=Fritzi Gordon

#Text=Fritzi Gordon ( 1905 or 1916 [ lower-alpha 1 ] – 8 February 1992 ) was an Austrian-born British bridge player , half of the most famous and tempestuous female partnership in the game 's history .
#Text=Following her long-time partner Rixi Markus , she was the second woman to attain the rank of WBF World Grand Master .
#Text=She won four world titles , eight European championships and numerous other tournaments .
#Text=Life
#Text=Gordon was born Frederika Leist in either Graz [ 1 ] [ lower-alpha 1 ] or Vienna to middle-class Jewish parents .
#Text=After school , she became the buyer for a Salzburg store , married Paul Gordon and moved to Graz .
#Text=The annexation of Austria by Germany in 1938 ( Anschluss ) disrupted her life , as it did to so many others .
#Text=She fled to London with her husband , though the details of this abrupt transition are not known .
#Text=Her brother , Dr. Hans Leist , also came to Britain .
#Text=( Also a fine bridge player , he was a member of five Gold Cup -winning teams between 1946 and 1953 . ) [ 2 ]
#Text=When Gordon left Austria , Markus recalled in her obituary tribute , " [ she ] was not known in the bridge world while I was already a world champion .

#Text=Their  discussions " at the table were quite famous , and earned them the soubriquets Frisky and Bitchy .

column1: #Text=Mrs Gordon was not a bridge writer and her private life remained private .
#Text=She is consequently the less well known of the pair . [ 4 ]
#Text=The actress Tara Summers is her granddaughter . [ 5 ]
#Text=In 2005 , Summers described in the Daily Telegraph the unusual circumstances in which her grandmother gave birth to her ( Summers ' ) mother : [ 6 ]
#Text=My mother was born under a poker table .
#Text=My grandmother , a world champion bridge player , had been dealt a royal flush just as she went into labour , and she chose to play the hand , rather than go to hospital .
#Text=She was excited about having a child but adamant that she was not going to let it get in the way of her game .
#Text=Her gambling addiction , although it may sound glamorous , proved to be just as damaging as any substance or alcohol dependency .
#Text=Bridge career
#Text=According to Truscott , Gordon had learned bridge from her brother Hans in Austria , and she was a " world-class player " by the end of the war . [ 1 ]
#Text=Even at the European-level , however , international competition resumed only with the 1948 European Bridge League championships .
#Text=Gordon 's tournament bridge career began after World War II , and her first partnership with Markus began half-way through the European Championships of 1950 .
#Text=In 1955 they agreed to form a regular partnership , [ 7 ]
#Text=which became one of the most successful women 's pairs in bridge history . [ 3 ]
#Text=The partnership lasted until 1975 .
#Text=Gordon won the World Women 's teams 1964 ; World Mixed teams 1962 ; World Women 's pairs 1962 and 1974 ( placed second in 1970 ) .
#Text=She won the European Women 's teams in 1950 , 1951 , 1952 , 1959 , 1961 , 1963 , 1966 and 1975 .
#Text=These were Britain 's first eight wins in the tournament , the 1975 win coming in her final appearance in the event . [ 8 ]
#Text=She represented Britain on nine other occasions and toured the USA in 1953 as part of the British women 's team .
#Text=Her national successes include the Gold Cup in 1957 and 1961 . [ 9 ]
#Text=Ewart Kempson thought she was " Our own greatest woman player , [ able ] to play on equal terms with the greatest men players " . [ 10 ]
#Text=Victor Mollo agreed that she played like a man :
#Text=" Few men play as well as Fritzi Gordon .
